The first thing to learn about Shoes is that you can stack things and then save them basically as an array. Since a binary clock has 6 columns, I created a variable </summary><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/9251785/8255526731750191731/comments/default' title='Post Comments'/><link rel='replies' type='text/html' href='https://www.blogger.com/comment.g?blogID=9251785&amp;postID=8255526731750191731' title='3 Comments'/><link rel='edit' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/9251785/posts/default/8255526731750191731'/><link rel='self' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/9251785/posts/default/8255526731750191731'/><link rel='alternate' type='text/html' href='http://www.cornetdesign.com/2008/09/binary-clock-in-ruby-using-shoes.html' title='A binary clock in Ruby using Shoes'/><author><name>Cory Foy</name><uri>http://www.blogger.com/profile/16623557184597571370</uri><email>noreply@blogger.com</email></author><thr:total xmlns:thr='http://purl.org/syndication/thread/1.0'>3</thr:total></entry><entry><id>tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-9251785.post-2129776838418327364</id><published>2008-09-12T21:53:00.003-05:00</published><updated>2008-09-12T22:10:40.369-05:00</updated><title type='text'>Clean Code Review</title><summary type='text'>As developers, system admins, and a variety of other roles in IT, we have to deal with code on a daily basis. Sometimes it's just one-off scripts we (hopefully) never have to see again. Sometimes (Ok, most of the time) we stare at something that, for the life of us, we can't understand how it came out of a human mind (or, as the book puts it, has a high WTF/minute count). But there is a time when</summary><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/9251785/2129776838418327364/comments/default' title='Post Comments'/><link rel='replies' type='text/html' href='https://www.blogger.com/comment.g?blogID=9251785&amp;postID=2129776838418327364' title='0 Comments'/><link rel='edit' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/9251785/posts/default/2129776838418327364'/><link rel='self' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/9251785/posts/default/2129776838418327364'/><link rel='alternate' type='text/html' href='http://www.cornetdesign.com/2008/09/clean-code-review.html' title='Clean Code Review'/><author><name>Cory Foy</name><uri>http://www.blogger.com/profile/16623557184597571370</uri><email>noreply@blogger.com</email></author><thr:total xmlns:thr='http://purl.org/syndication/thread/1.0'>0</thr:total></entry><entry><id>tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-9251785.post-214104729151057039</id><published>2008-09-02T00:32:00.001-05:00</published><updated>2008-09-02T00:32:15.067-05:00</updated><title type='text'>When Planning Games Go Too Long</title><summary type='text'>This topic has come up in several of my readings today. While I've seen several strategies for what to do when your planning game is going too long, the best one is perhaps the simplest, and comes from none other than Ron Jeffries on the Scrum Development mailing list:


I suspect you're going into way too much detail. And if you
over-commit, so what? Learn from it.

Try planning poker.

